Wikipedia procedures preempt consensus when rules are contravened. This contrived statement comprises an inappropriate synthesis of sources to conflate institutional image. I hold your alma mater in high repute, but I implore you to stop edit warring.

The phrase "world's most prestigious" is an editorialized extrapolation used as a proxy for institutional quality. [[WP:UNIGUIDE]] states "do not use rankings to synthesize an image of the institution" especially without "numeric values with years".
In accordance with [[WP:UNIGUIDE]], rankings should be narrowly tailored,  "precise and honest", and "reported as numeric values with years."

The "every article is to blame so none are guilty" argument is not cogent, nor does it justify contravening WP rules. Similar statements are being deleted in several articles of "high ranking" universities, including this one.

The "every article is to blame so none are guilty" argument is not cogent, nor does it justify contravening WP rules. Similar statements are being deleted in several articles of "high ranking" universities, including this one.

The phrase "world's best universities" is an editorialized extrapolation used as a proxy for institutional quality. [[WP:UNIGUIDE]] states "do not use rankings to synthesize an image of the institution" especially without "numeric values with years"

Beyond being overtly boosterish, this statement constitutes, under [[WP:UNIGUIDE]], an implicit proxy of institutional quality, and thus imposes [[Wikipedia:Reliable sources and undue weight|undue weight]] on the sources cited.

[[WP:UNIGUIDE]] states: "Claims that an institution "ranks highly" or is "highly exclusive" are just as vague as claims that it is "prestigious" and "excellent."... In the lead, do not use rankings to synthesize an image of the institution..."
